1. FREE FOR INDIVIDUALS AND SMALL TEAMS (Qartez Small Team License)
==========================================================================

Subject to the terms below, permission is hereby granted, free of charge,
to any Eligible User obtaining a copy of this software and associated
documentation files (the "Software") to use, copy, modify, and distribute
the Software for any purpose, including personal, educational, open-source,
hobby, and commercial use.

DEFINITIONS

"Use" means any interaction with the Software that benefits You or Your
Company, including running it locally as a development tool while
authoring code or content that is later sold, licensed, or distributed.

"Your Company" means the individual, legal entity, sole proprietorship,
partnership, or other organization on whose behalf You Use the Software.
When Your Company is a legal entity, Your Company also includes all
organizations that have control over, are under the control of, or are
under common control with that entity. Control means ownership of
substantially all the assets of an entity, or the power to direct its
management and policies by vote, contract, or otherwise. Control can be
direct or indirect.

A single-member LLC, sole proprietorship, or equivalent legal wrapper
around one individual counts as that one individual for the purposes of
counting Users. An individual acting alone, with no associated legal
entity, is treated as Your Company of one.

"Users" means the total number of distinct individuals within Your
Company who regularly Use the Software, counted over any rolling ninety
(90) day period. Employees, contractors, founders, and owners who
interact with the Software as part of their normal workflow are counted.
An individual who interacts with the Software only incidentally (for
example, to evaluate, test, troubleshoot a one-off integration, or
attend a demo) and does not make the Software part of their regular
workflow is not counted as a User. Individuals at Your Company who do
not interact with the Software at all are not counted.

"Annual Revenue" means Your Company's gross commercial revenue in the
prior fiscal year, measured in United States dollars using the exchange
rate published by the United States Federal Reserve H.10 Daily Rates on
the last business day of that fiscal year. Commercial revenue includes
product sales, subscription fees, consulting fees, licensing fees,
royalties, and advertising revenue. Commercial revenue does not include
grants, donations, sponsorships, or crowdfunding contributions received
in support of open-source work. For the first fiscal year of Your
Company's existence, Annual Revenue is deemed to be zero.

ELIGIBILITY

You qualify as an Eligible User if both of the following are true:

(a) Your Company has three (3) or fewer Users, AND
(b) Your Company's Annual Revenue is less than one million United States
    dollars ($1,000,000 USD).

EXAMPLES OF PERMITTED USE

The following are explicitly permitted under the free tier and require no
Commercial License:

- A solo developer using the Software to author open-source or commercial
  code on their own machine.
- A single-member LLC, sole proprietorship, or equivalent legal wrapper
  around one individual, using the Software for its own projects.
- A student using the Software for coursework, research, or learning.
- A two-person cofounder team using the Software on their development
  machines to build a product they later sell, as long as Your Company's
  Annual Revenue remains under the threshold. Accepting investment does
  not affect Eligibility; commercial revenue does.
- A three-person startup using the Software internally, as long as
  Annual Revenue is under the threshold. Funding stage and legal
  structure do not affect Eligibility.
- An open-source maintainer using the Software to work on a project that
  accepts donations, grants, sponsorship, or paid content tiers. Such
  income does not count toward Annual Revenue.
- A team of any size where three or fewer members actually interact with
  the Software. Users are counted by active seats, not by headcount of
  Your Company.
- Using the Software in Your Company's CI/CD pipelines, development
  machines, or internal build servers to analyze Your Company's own
  code, as an extension of local development tool use.

